💻 Laptop Market Insights: Analyzing Specifications & Prices¶

🎯 Objective¶

Have you ever wondered which laptop specifications impact the price the most? Or which brands offer the best value for money? This notebook dives into the laptop market, breaking down key specifications and trends to uncover valuable insights.

🔍 What's Inside?¶

We'll explore a dataset containing details such as:
✅ Brands (Dell, HP, Apple, etc.)
✅ Processors (Intel, AMD, Apple M-series)
✅ RAM & Storage (How much is enough?)
✅ Graphics Cards (Gaming vs. Everyday Use)
✅ Pricing Trends (What makes a laptop expensive?)

📊 How We'll Analyze the Data¶

  • Data Preprocessing & Cleaning 🛠️
  • Visualizing Trends & Patterns 📈
  • Identifying Price-Performance Relationships 🔎
  • Finding the Best Value Laptops (Optional) 💰

By the end of this notebook, you'll have a data-driven perspective on the laptop market, helping you make better purchasing or business decisions.

✲ There are 1303 and 12 columns.

•Unnamed: The index of the dataset.

•Company: The brand or manufacturer of the laptop.

•TypeName: The category or type of the laptop.

•Inches: The size of the laptop's screen, measured in inches.

•ScreenResolution: The screen resolution of the laptop.

•Cpu: The processor in the laptop, including its model and speed.

•Ram: The amount of RAM in the laptop, typically measured in GB.

•Memory: The storage capacity of the laptop, either in SSD or HDD.

•Gpu: The type of graphics processing unit (GPU) installed in the laptop.

•OpSys: The operating system of the laptop.

•Weight: The weight of the laptop in kilograms.

•Price: The price of the laptop in the dataset.

#Remove unwanted characters and convert to appropriate type
df.Weight=df.Weight.str.strip("kg").astype("float")

df["Price"]=df["Price"].round(2)

df['Ram'] = df['Ram'].str.replace('GB', '').astype(int)

df['MemorySize'] = df['Memory'].str.extract(r'(\d+GB)') 
df['MemoryType'] = df['Memory'].str.extract(r'\d+GB\s*(.*)')

df.drop(columns=["Memory"],inplace=True)

In [73]:
#The ScreenResolution column was split into two new columns: PanelType and Resolution. 
#The original column was then dropped, and PanelType was cleaned and updated to include whether the device has a touchscreen (Yes or No)
df['PanelType'] = df['ScreenResolution'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x.split()[:-1]))
df['Resolution'] = df['ScreenResolution'].apply(lambda x: x.split()[-1])

df.drop(columns="ScreenResolution",inplace=True)

df['PanelType'] = df['PanelType'].str.replace("IPS Panel", "", regex=False).str.strip()
df['Touchscreen'] = df['PanelType'].apply(lambda x: 'Yes' if 'Touchscreen' in x else 'No')

df['PanelType'] = df['PanelType'].str.replace(" / Touchscreen", "", regex=False).str.strip()
df['PanelType'] = df['PanelType'].replace('', 'Unknown')

•Weight and screen size (Inches) have weak correlations with price (0.15 and 0.02, respectively), suggesting that these features are less influential in determining cost.

•Additionally, weight and screen size are strongly correlated (0.83), reflecting that larger laptops tend to weigh more. This analysis highlights RAM as a key driver of pricing.

📌CONCLUSION

✲The analysis provides valuable insights into the laptop market. Key findings include:

✔Price Influencers: RAM size, storage type, and panel quality significantly affect laptop pricing, with higher configurations leading to higher costs.

✔Dominant Features: Touchscreens and 8GB RAM are prevalent, reflecting their popularity among users.

✔Market Trends: Windows is the most widely used operating system, and Intel dominates the CPU and GPU space.

✔Diversity: Gaming laptops and workstations are priced higher, catering to niche, high-performance markets, while netbooks target budget users.

✲These insights highlight trends in the laptop market, helping to understand pricing strategies and consumer preferences.
